  "summary": "Following an observation by Hastings regarding the alphabetical order of the victims' names, Hercule Poirot claims to have discovered the true motive behind the killer's choices, including the selection of Mrs. Asher, Sir Charles Clarke, and the staging of the murder at Tengcombe. Poirot intends to gather information from the Special Branch before confronting the \"ABC\" killer through a conversation designed to reveal the truth through lies.\n\nAccompanied by Hastings and a special group, Poirot conducts an investigation in Bexhill. He interviews Mrs. Bardner regarding Alexander Bonaparte Cast, visits the hotel where Cast stayed, and examines the beach where Betty Bardner's body was discovered. He also observes the route from the beach to the Eastbourne bus station. After a brief stop at the Golden Cat Cafe, where he flirts with a waitress named Milly Higley, Poirot travels to Eastbourne for further investigation.\n\nAt the hotel, Franklin Clarke suggests that Poirot is merely attempting to destroy evidence regarding the killer's whereabouts. In response, Poirot proposes a game of \"Truth or Dare,\" requiring everyone present to swear to tell the truth. Poirot asks Franklin Clarke a trivial question about hats at the Ascot race and questions Donald Fraser about his holiday schedule, which causes Fraser visible distress. He then asks Tara Grey if she would marry Sir Charles Clarke if Lady Clark were to die; Grey refuses, citing her feelings for Sir Michael. Finally, Poirot sharply asks Megan Bard if she wants the investigation to reveal the truth.",
